<subSubSection id="E6BD4A1E60FD6EB5AD1F71110DD084F3" pageId="2" pageNumber="19" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="F40F31366E1BDB9FE747E7671337A8B4" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A7902BADA1DF2D748549E4D2D4BC7841" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">plicata - folded or pleated.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CD94842C89B83A21F95E5B50A76B8BB5" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="22" pageId="2" pageNumber="19" type="description">
<paragraph id="97A793B80EB08FAFE52EAD054F284683" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8EF6386692A7012F83C63286ED5BE4FD" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">
The blades of 
<taxonomicName id="1D24073DD3CA1FD1AE14F6C2C0A3012E" authorityName="W. A. Nelson" authorityYear="2013" class="Bangiophyceae" family="Bangiaceae" genus="Pyropia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Bangiales" pageId="2" pageNumber="19" phylum="Rhodophyta" rank="species" species="plicata">
<emphasis id="264B37DF9D2F294456E365578CCBBF98" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">Pyropia plicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are deeply folded and when fully extended are seen to have a circular to oval shape. The blades are very variable in size, generally in the range of 4-12 cm in diameter although reproductively mature thalli have been found to range from 1.5 cm through to 42 cm in diameter. The thalli are attached to rock substrata by a centrally located holdfast, made up of rhizoids extending from cells in the lower (central) area of the blade. The thalli are robust and very strongly attached to rock substrata in the upper intertidal zone of rocky open coasts (
<figureCitation id="E181591AEF93F9C41E953673E6ACBAA6" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Pyropia plicata exposed at low tide on upper intertidal rocks (ca 5 cm high)." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10246" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">Figure 2</figureCitation>
). Thalli are primarily purple to grey in colour, but they become bleached particularly in summer and autumn and become khaki to yellow-green particularly on the upper edges.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="626761C2E08DEAF54AE76F7FBF3353CD" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">
Thalli are monostromatic and monoecious. Sterile regions of the blades are ca. 50-55 
<normalizedToken id="BDD55D5DDF72D1D1A898B4D4D8B93831" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
thick and the margin of the blade has a ragged or irregular appearance bordered by several layers of small pale cells (
<figureCitation id="5146F8EB55200B9169814DC73729D654" captionStart="Figure 3–4" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3 - 4. 3 (left): Vegetative region of the blade showing the margin with small pale cells. (WELT A 032593) 4 (right): Fertile region of the blade with packets of developing zygotosporangia (larger, darker-coloured clusters), single sterile cells (between zygotosporangia) and packets of spermatangia (smaller, paler-coloured clusters) releasing at the blade margin. (WELT A 032593). Scale bar = 50 µm." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10247" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">Figure 3</figureCitation>
). Fertile regions of the blade develop around the margins with sterile cells intermixed with patches of spermatangia and presumed zygotosporangia (
<figureCitation id="A4B79F6C6A79D397D22AF0D873707525" captionStart="Figure 3–4" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3 - 4. 3 (left): Vegetative region of the blade showing the margin with small pale cells. (WELT A 032593) 4 (right): Fertile region of the blade with packets of developing zygotosporangia (larger, darker-coloured clusters), single sterile cells (between zygotosporangia) and packets of spermatangia (smaller, paler-coloured clusters) releasing at the blade margin. (WELT A 032593). Scale bar = 50 µm." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10247" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">Figure 4</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4B42F6C260E7584C79C10CBB6669FF9C" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="20" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">
In the early stages of development spindle-shaped carpogonia form trichogynes on both sides of the blade, in marked contrast to the box-like shape of the neighbouring sterile cells (
<figureCitation id="611A6773CD5B38BEAC9E5C587B30A544" captionStart="Figure 5–7" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 5 - 7. 5 Cross section of monostromatic blade showing square sterile cells and spindle-shaped developing carpogonia. (WELT A 032593) 6 Cross section view of mature zygotosporangia. (WELT A 032593) 7 Cross section view of mature spermatangia. (WELT A 032593). Scale bar 5: 50 µm, 6 - 7: 20 µm." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10248" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">Figure 5</figureCitation>
). Blades increase in thickness to ca. 85-110 
<normalizedToken id="097CEF4350D06B43272B462BF996C20C" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
in zygotosporangial regions (
<figureCitation id="E80C8A8DE7A3EFA387C8B45C2C268C2F" captionStart="Figure 5–7" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 5 - 7. 5 Cross section of monostromatic blade showing square sterile cells and spindle-shaped developing carpogonia. (WELT A 032593) 6 Cross section view of mature zygotosporangia. (WELT A 032593) 7 Cross section view of mature spermatangia. (WELT A 032593). Scale bar 5: 50 µm, 6 - 7: 20 µm." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10248" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">Figure 6</figureCitation>
) and ca. 60-70 
<normalizedToken id="85845BF766626BD4805555FD4115F3A8" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
in mature spermatangial regions 
<pageBreakToken id="F50369DC4319F24EA99B38C2AC9E4108" pageId="3" pageNumber="20" start="start">(</pageBreakToken>
<figureCitation id="82E6D18875BF9D6752B3927C27E7F56D" captionStart="Figure 5–7" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 5 - 7. 5 Cross section of monostromatic blade showing square sterile cells and spindle-shaped developing carpogonia. (WELT A 032593) 6 Cross section view of mature zygotosporangia. (WELT A 032593) 7 Cross section view of mature spermatangia. (WELT A 032593). Scale bar 5: 50 µm, 6 - 7: 20 µm." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10248" pageId="3" pageNumber="20">Figure 7</figureCitation>
). The zygotosporangia when mature are deep red and the packets vary in size, becoming lozenge shaped at maturity with divisions up to a/8, b/8, c/8 (
<figureCitation id="9EB2BD43F02771ACB82485C97A00D63F" captionStart="Figure 5–7" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 5 - 7. 5 Cross section of monostromatic blade showing square sterile cells and spindle-shaped developing carpogonia. (WELT A 032593) 6 Cross section view of mature zygotosporangia. (WELT A 032593) 7 Cross section view of mature spermatangia. (WELT A 032593). Scale bar 5: 50 µm, 6 - 7: 20 µm." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10248" pageId="3" pageNumber="20">Figure 6</figureCitation>
). The spermatangial patches become golden as they develop and when mature are divided into packets ca. a/2, b/2, c/8 (
<figureCitation id="6D0762388E7D8BFA9859F545B09B80EC" captionStart="Figure 5–7" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 5 - 7. 5 Cross section of monostromatic blade showing square sterile cells and spindle-shaped developing carpogonia. (WELT A 032593) 6 Cross section view of mature zygotosporangia. (WELT A 032593) 7 Cross section view of mature spermatangia. (WELT A 032593). Scale bar 5: 50 µm, 6 - 7: 20 µm." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10248" pageId="3" pageNumber="20">Figure 7</figureCitation>
). Spermatia and zygotospores are usually released before reaching the maximum division formulae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9DA0765139A395383C3030BC1563C3E0" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="21" pageId="3" pageNumber="20">
Typically 
<taxonomicName id="7BEA4DE816138B9799454F28152C9350" authorityName="W. A. Nelson" authorityYear="2013" class="Bangiophyceae" family="Bangiaceae" genus="Pyropia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Bangiales" pageId="3" pageNumber="20" phylum="Rhodophyta" rank="species" species="plicata">
<emphasis id="3D611CA04541A016EE166A41FC8E63A0" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="20">Pyropia plicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is found on the upper intertidal shores of open coasts on rocky substrata. It has not been found growing epiphytically and is uncommon in sheltered areas. The deep pleats and central attachment of 
<taxonomicName id="C9BD6B0349C363D6CB4D84719A8677C7" authorityName="W. A. Nelson" authorityYear="2013" class="Bangiophyceae" family="Bangiaceae" genus="Pyropia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Bangiales" pageId="3" pageNumber="20" phylum="Rhodophyta" rank="species" species="plicata">
<emphasis id="E5F1ABA502048AE1B3690DD382D22C88" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="20">Pyropia plicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
enable the retention of moisture between the folds in the blade. This morphology would appear 
<pageBreakToken id="F78F6CA981E5CF59174CF02AB70183F8" pageId="4" pageNumber="21" start="start">to</pageBreakToken>
be advantageous in the upper intertidal habitats where it is found, as this species can be out of water for periods of up to eight hours between tidal cycles. The outer part of a clump of 
<taxonomicName id="BD46B25C64E53812694FD4A180658C77" authorityName="W. A. Nelson" authorityYear="2013" class="Bangiophyceae" family="Bangiaceae" genus="Pyropia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Bangiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="21" phylum="Rhodophyta" rank="species" species="plicata">
<emphasis id="D3CEA54CBFCF275E26B337543ABFA0BB" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="21">Pyropia plicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be dried with a cellophane-like appearance yet within the folds, parts of the blade remain wet.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1DCFD56170CD9AC098C57C6C2C7D4C69" pageId="4" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicName id="A9EA07D5881A024A0158DA9C79E4C76E" authorityName="W. A. Nelson" authorityYear="2013" class="Bangiophyceae" family="Bangiaceae" genus="Pyropia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Bangiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="21" phylum="Rhodophyta" rank="species" species="plicata">
<emphasis id="182997B8D9BD7A482F83D0970D88722B" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="21">Pyropia plicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shows no particular seasonal trends in its distribution, with reproductively mature specimens collected throughout the year. Collections of this species have been made from the northern tip of the North Island, through to areas on the south western and south eastern South Island, as well as on the Chatham Islands. It has not been found on the Three Kings Islands, Stewart Island, or any of the New Zealand subantarctic islands.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="44B7D83F38E50349BA168EBDE520F5DF" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="22" pageId="4" pageNumber="21">
Distinctive features: 
<taxonomicName id="F2B5625E9FB32D2B2DC63BD0556A009D" authorityName="W. A. Nelson" authorityYear="2013" class="Bangiophyceae" family="Bangiaceae" genus="Pyropia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Bangiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="21" phylum="Rhodophyta" rank="species" species="plicata">
<emphasis id="5642A7DDB8CA87817EAF4E7C3892C676" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="21">Pyropia plicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from other New Zealand species of bladed Bangiales by a number of distinctive features. It is the only species of 
<taxonomicName id="589A9911DCA557E03E0D61D4A2E18CD3" authorityName="J.Agardh" authorityYear="1899" class="Bangiophyceae" family="Bangiaceae" genus="Pyropia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Bangiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="21" phylum="Rhodophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="D978F6B6F3441C5FC4A831AC088BC6FC" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="21">Pyropia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
present on mainland shores with a marked rosette-like growth form. Although the ribbon-like blades of 
<taxonomicName id="2B7679B33DCCA394101236B29757721C" class="Bangiophyceae" family="Bangiaceae" genus="Pyropia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Bangiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="21" phylum="Rhodophyta" rank="species" species="cinnamomea">
<emphasis id="273064B9EC74F971D831EB245B036422" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="21">Pyropia cinnamomea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may become eroded with age, the basal position of the holdfast in this species differs from 
<taxonomicName id="A45F1B04125E4969FF61235B527EE08A" authorityName="W. A. Nelson" authorityYear="2013" class="Bangiophyceae" family="Bangiaceae" genus="Pyropia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Bangiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="21" phylum="Rhodophyta" rank="species" species="plicata">
<emphasis id="459BA12F27B113BFC7F48D74420ACC99" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="21">Pyropia plicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In addition, these two species can 
<pageBreakToken id="DD0C75CC7438278F3B58C7FECA24C69D" pageId="5" pageNumber="22" start="start">be</pageBreakToken>
distinguished by colour, and also by the division formulae of zygotosporangia. On intertidal shores 
<taxonomicName id="0A87C2E20F5A34FCF0B8D0161EBCEF0E" authorityName="W. A. Nelson" authorityYear="2013" class="Bangiophyceae" family="Bangiaceae" genus="Pyropia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Bangiales" pageId="5" pageNumber="22" phylum="Rhodophyta" rank="species" species="plicata">
<emphasis id="FC633A64F068CF7C3D6388547CC59896" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="22">Pyropia plicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characteristically found in the high intertidal but below the position occupied by 
<taxonomicName id="3E5B314FDC3C8B5A83E8272AFA82208C" class="Polychaeta" family="Maldanidae" genus="Clymene" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Not" pageId="5" pageNumber="22" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="coleana">
<emphasis id="07FFCC400FA9954984A404B93DA62C99" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="22">Clymene coleana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(W.A.Nelson) W.A.Nelson from which it can be easily distinguished. 
<taxonomicName id="2FBB6F13624FC07715F462CC24A82FBA" class="Polychaeta" family="Maldanidae" genus="Clymene" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Not" pageId="5" pageNumber="22" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="coleana">
<emphasis id="DB16C4B74A8A755A58CAC4B79652D8D9" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="22">Clymene coleana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has finely divided finger-like lobes rather than the continuous circular to oval deeply pleated blade of 
<taxonomicName id="2E600BA7835C30AAAF2E5BBAFC066984" authorityName="W. A. Nelson" authorityYear="2013" class="Bangiophyceae" family="Bangiaceae" genus="Pyropia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Bangiales" pageId="5" pageNumber="22" phylum="Rhodophyta" rank="species" species="plicata">
<emphasis id="9E708D6E963F79508C689C7301C1BF30" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="22">Pyropia plicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Although both of these species have a predominantly grey colour in winter months, they bleach to different colours in bright light, with 
<taxonomicName id="5B2E48FA1A3CE4B9747768D551208086" class="Polychaeta" family="Maldanidae" genus="Clymene" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Not" pageId="5" pageNumber="22" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="coleana">
<emphasis id="FFBCDD9A0311DD3E057DF46D7B289344" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="22">Clymene coleana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
becoming golden compared with the khaki colour of 
<taxonomicName id="90D5762EF330FA9008D18B131014D683" authorityName="W. A. Nelson" authorityYear="2013" class="Bangiophyceae" family="Bangiaceae" genus="Pyropia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Bangiales" pageId="5" pageNumber="22" phylum="Rhodophyta" rank="species" species="plicata">
<emphasis id="E514E94095BBDF55F9CCCC524BD20452" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="22">Pyropia plicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In addition the zygotosporangia and spermatangia are arranged in separate areas of the blade in 
<taxonomicName id="0583A905CEE4EDCDB435AF5B7B644EE6" class="Polychaeta" family="Maldanidae" genus="Clymene" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Not" pageId="5" pageNumber="22" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="coleana">
<emphasis id="4D0B1CA98B0218EB1BE85942415D718C" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="22">Clymene coleana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
rather than being intermixed in 
<taxonomicName id="EE93EAFE610B5D2628A86B60F8AF176C" class="Polychaeta" family="Maldanidae" genus="Clymene" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Not" pageId="5" pageNumber="22" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="plicata">
<emphasis id="8432D902D65B5DCF7210048F2D5CB610" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="22">Clymene plicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
